Casestudy: Exploration of flights dataset

5 11 2018

Purpose and research question

Suppose we are interested in the following question:

What are the causes of flights delays?

Unfortunately, we have only observational data, so there is little hope of finding causal roots of delays. But what we can hope to achieve is an understanding of predictors (in the statistical sense, not causal sense) of delays.

Again, quite a bit of variation is present. Of central interest is of course the response variable, delay. We see that there are two variants of delay: arrival and departure delay. Which one is more important? It probably depends on my view: Sitting in the delayed plain, Im interested in how much later the machines touches ground (arrival delay). Sitting at the gate, Im hoping to get aboard as soon as possible (departure delay). Maybe departure delay is the more conservative choice: assuming that departure delay is arrival delay plus possible additional delay during ground stay, we may chose to look at departure delay.

Start modeling

We have already stated modeling! In the last step above we reasoned that the origin of a flight may be a source of variation in delay time. Probably, we even considered the origin as a cause of delay. This makes sense (or is plausible at least) from a theoretical point of view. Sadly, the data does not allow for such strong conclusions. Maybe we may speak of candidate causes here.

More formally, one could write:

delay = f(origin)

In other words, the (departure) delay is some (unknown) function of the origin.

In Rs modeling language, we would translate the equation above as:

dep_delay ~ origin

Lets be more precise and argue that we think there is a difference in means between the origins:

#> # A tibble: 3 x 5
#>   term        estimate std.error statistic   p.value
#>   <chr>          <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>
#> 1 (Intercept)    15.0      0.117     128.  0.       
#> 2 originJFK      -2.99     0.168     -17.7 2.65e- 70
#> 3 originLGA      -4.72     0.172     -27.5 3.33e-166

The results show us, one the one hand, the same as the summary (via mean()) above. But, on the other hand, do infer that the differences between the means are substantial and should be expected to happen in future samples, too. More on that later.

Is distance an important predictor of delay?

By flight

One may argue that the farer away the destination, the more likely something happens, resulting in (more) delay. Lets check that. First, visually:

Due to the quite large data set, the ggplot() plotting takes a while. Maybe it would be practical to see if we can get the same (or similar) results based on a smaller sample?

In essence, the scatterplot above suggests that airtime plays no role. That means that the correlation should be (close to) zero:

As shown by the scatterplot, theres no bivariate correlation. Notice that we are only looking at lineare covariation and that we did not take any other variables into account (possibly altering the association).

Again, instead of correlating the two variables, it is more useful to model delay as a function of distance:

#> # A tibble: 4 x 5
#>   term             estimate std.error statistic   p.value
#>   <chr>               <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>

#> 4 originLGA           -5.21    0.174      -29.9 3.80e-196

The output tells us that - if anything - the delay shrinks by some 1.6 minutes for each 1000 km flown. In comparision to Newark, JFK and LGA are somewhat more delayed, holding constants the distance of the flights from each origin.

Again, there appears to be no strong pattern, no strong assocation.

Stop and think

Our searching was not really successful so far. We have not identified important sources of variation in delay. Lets recknognize this fact.

Second, we should recknognize that we are quite explorative: Theres no strong theory guiding our statistical analysis. It is probably true that many other analysis in the social sciences suffer from this problem, but it is still undesirable. Given one applies statistical magigcal sauce long enough, some effects are bound to pop up. We would have move more confidence in our results if they were driven by a strong theory. Otherwise we are prone to overfit the data.

Given the lack of a theory that tells us which predictors are important, what to do? There are of course a number of statistical approaches for selecting predictors including stepwise procedures, considering the bivariate correlation, variable importance of machine learning approaches, information criteria, and more.

However, a theory based approach has the advantage of better understanding what we are modeling, of being able of making sense of it and thus possibly using it elsewhere including explaining it to someone.

Now, the idea of blaiming the nature for the delays have failed. It is not the weather, as it appears, nor the distance, nor the time of the year. So, it it is not nature, it must be human made. Although we are lacking data to fully explore the faultyness of human nature, we can at least check how much variation is explained by using the destination as predictor. The rationale is here that some folks at some places do it well, whereas other folks at other places (destinations) have other things to do (and thus produce delays).

The human-made-disaster hypothesis

Lets call the human-made-disaster hypothesis the belief, that delay is human made, somehow. We dont exacly know how, but we speculate people have different ability in (not) producing delay. Further, we assume that some places, being complex systems with complex interactions, are more competent in producing delays. On this base, we reckon that the differences between destinations (and secondly, origins) explain a big part of the observed delays. On a similar base, the persons at the carriers (airlines) may exert an impact on the delays.

#> [1] 0.01461551

Sadly, this hypothesis does not explain much of the delays either.

Theres one more important source of humanness: the pilot. Unfortunately, we dont have data on that. Maybe we can use the tail number of a plain as a proxy assuming that one pilot tends to use the same machine.

Before we start: how many different machines are there?

#> [1] 4044

Quite a bit. How many machines do operate often and how many do not leave their parking lot? To make things quicker, lets focus on those who have flown at least 100 times.

The date-time hypothesis

Another frequent idea is that delay times build up over the days, so thats time of the day which is responsible for delays.
